message.content:
In any derivation the start symbol expands as  

S ⇒ NT9 NT3  

so every generated string is the concatenation of what NT9 produces (first) followed by what NT3 produces (second).  
Therefore the very first terminal of every string in the language must be the first terminal that NT9 can generate.

Look at the possible productions for NT9:

NT9 → NT8 NT4  
NT9 → NT7 NT1  
NT9 → NT2 NT8  
NT9 → NT8 NT1  
NT9 → 't16'

The left-hand nonterminal in each two-symbol production (NT8, NT7 or NT2) is the source of the first terminal, or the single–terminal production gives 't16' directly.

• NT8 can ultimately yield only t26, t11 or t10 (it never yields t28).  
• NT7 yields t0.  
• NT2 yields t24.  
• The single-terminal production yields t16.

Hence the first terminal symbol that NT9 can ever produce is limited to {t26, t11, t10, t0, t24, t16}.  
t28 is not among them.

The string we are asked to recognise begins with t28.  
Since t28 cannot be the first symbol produced by NT9, the start symbol S cannot generate this string.

Therefore the given grammar does not generate the provided string.

No
